Good game.

A good resource management game which will suck up hours of your time like 
all good such games do, think anno for mobile. Good: 1. Lovely visuals, 
cute styling 2. Detailed management sim with all the standard items like 
houses, workers, castle, hunting, gathering, luxuries etc to manage. 3. 
Marketplace to buy and sell goods is extremely useful and allows for 
specialisation 4. Leveling up functionality, quests and scenarios encourage 
you to keep playing. 5. Good challenge, even for veteran players of the 
genre, esp at the early stages of the game. Bad: 1. No clear data on how 
much each building produces in how much time or how much is consumed by 
people in the game makes planning your city a combination of guesswork and 
experience. No production stats available to properly manage your

Seriously, the gameplay is hilariously horrible and broken. It starts out 
fun and maybe a little hard until you realize just how broken it is. Why? 
The happiness mechanic just does not work. You can keep your people starved 
to death with no water to drink and they will still keep paying maximum 
taxes. If things go awry, just lower taxes and make them work. Even with no 
food or water at all you can have prosperous 500+ metropolis if you just 
keep hammering on those taxes and buying new houses. Several annoying 
mechanics also include limited trading (so you end up with huge stacks of 
resources clogging your buildings that you can't get rid off), broken 
prestige system (I playedabout ten hours total and had 700+ prestige and 
nothing to do with it, so why buy any?) Or the inability to replace sick 
workers with healthy ones (so they just keep necessary buildings occupied 
and you cannot do anything about it) or the stupid decoration mechanic 
(just build mausoleums and graves everywhere and people will love you, 
because hey, it's a decoration!). However the worst is the total lack of 
challenge once you research a few upgrades. I had like 200k+ of cash and 
nothing to do with it and there was no possible threat. No disasters, no 
enemy countries no lack of resources, just nothing. So I abandoned the 
city. Stopped repairing and even destroyed the city wells and it still took 
10 seasons(!!!) for the city to burn down. TLDR fun for the first 4-5 
hours, but the system is totally broken and gamable. Pick up Caesar 3, or 
even SimCity or anything else instead

This game is a solid app that I highly suggest. I'll give you three reasons why:  1. The gameplay requires micromanagement but has a goal. The different buildings are generally the same but have chains or different effects on your town so they feel unique.  2. The graphics are good, reliable and nostalgic.  3. There are a lot of options for repeatability. With the levelling system and system-wide research the game will keep you busy with managing resources to both monopolize your town or research certain perks such as increased productivity for food buildings or increased range for fire towers.

Pros: Complex and detailed game.  A lot to do, very smooth and nice graphics and gameplay.  A lot of work has been put into this game, you can see it everywhere.  The game is challenging (takes some time to get a grip on it all) and absorbing, yet the feel of it all is delicate and relaxing.  Good music and effects really absorb me.  You can play the game with your physical mouse - I'm using a Bluetooth mouse, and I think it's easier + you can see more on the screen.  The game is in landscape mode.  Cons: at game startup you have this promo screen about other games by this dev and you have to click to proceed, and every time when the game resources load you have to press a button to proceed.  For me it's irritating, tiering and time-consuming.

You are limited as to the amount of videos you can watch each day to earn prestige. The offers are, in my opinion, very shady. However, it is now possible to succeed in this game without spending money, you just have to be very patient.

Good game for the simple fact you don't wait for hours or even days for buildings to finish like most city building games. The tutorial could be a lot better. You need wheat to make flour, and flour to make bread....so you need a building for each one (3) of those.  Same basic principle for all other resources in the game and the tutorial doesn't do a good job of explaining that.  The diagrams on the building info panel help a little but can be clarified a bit, like showing what product(s) come in and whats coming out and how many.  It sort of does that but doesn't seem like anythings in order, and an =  would seem less confusing then an arrow (to me).  There's 30 different resources on the resource page just listed one after the other in somewhat of an order.   It would be less confusing if they where classified then sub classified.  Like if I needed more bread, under bread it would show how much flour and wheat I have total instead of flipping through pages on the resouce section.  Out room.  Not bad game tho.

Well done game with minor flaws. The UI is clean and works smoothly, the graphics are quite nice, the BGM is fitting and doesn't get annoying too quickly.  The most important part - the gameplay - is mostly decent; various production chains and resource management not even badly balanced. Some details could be improved, e.g. map rotation to make building easier ( and to get a better view); a different savegame system that allows multiple slots for one city. But my major complaint are the IAPs that just feel wrong in this game. By design there is too much micromanagement that _should_ be automated by certain (building) upgrades but guess what? There is the inevitable second in game currency... I wouldn't mind spending a few bucks more for a complete game but this is just the wrong way to handle it. The game is still fun and can be played without spending additional money so I still rate it 4 stars but the timed ads and the unnecessary IAPs damage a potentially great game. It's still a decent one though.

This game is worth the $3.    It's a pretty basic Sim-type game that I find satisfying.  It's NOT in-depth or difficult, but if you are looking for a light, simple game with just enough going on to scratch the "Sim-Itch" - this is the game for you.    The graphics are decent - although a bit of the "cutesy" side for me.  When you get a town built, there's a LOT going on - people running around, birds flying over, wild-life around town, wind in the trees. Honestly, it is probably overkill but it does feel "alive" once you get going with it.  I can't say much for sound because I mute the game. (Better for playing in the bathroom stalls etc! )  Game-play is good.  There are a few issues:  The first is you can't rotate the screen which would be nice from a view-perspective and functionally to help you place things correctly.  Second, I've noticed that sometimes townies become "trapped" and despite there being a path available - they don't seem to find it.  Third, sometimes placing things can be hard if you have to scroll around the screen at all.   None of these things breaks the game.  Overall, I can definitely recommend this game and personally I think it is worth the price.
